06:10.221 --> 06:20.633
This history then is a prologue of the Bureau of 
Ships, a record of wartime accomplishments

06:10.221 --> 06:20.633
almost unequal in scope, integration, and 
success of mission. According to the extensive

06:21.322 --> 06:43.937
data presented in the preceding chapters, the 
Bureau's functions in attaining these

06:21.322 --> 06:43.937
accomplishments during the fiery months from 7 
December 1941

06:21.322 --> 06:43.937
to 14 August 1945 fell into the categories of 
planning, production, and maintenance, which

06:21.322 --> 06:43.937
may well be recapitulated briefly to describe the 
background from which the future will emanate.

06:45.622 --> 06:51.432
One element of planning involved the efficacious 
allocation of over 20 billions of dollars during

06:45.622 --> 06:51.432
the war period. This sum went into the purchase of 
12 million tons of steel, an intake conservation

06:52.153 --> 07:11.005
of critical materials program which saved 30 
million pounds of nickel, 20 million pounds of

06:52.153 --> 07:11.005
rubber, 9 million pounds of tin, 207 million 
pounds of copper, and resulted in a considerable

06:52.153 --> 07:11.005
financial economy. It went into wages for some one 
million shipyard workers at the program's peak

07:11.356 --> 07:21.082
load, with over two million industrial workers 
being engaged in satellite industries at this

07:11.356 --> 07:21.082
same moment. Two million dollars were used to 
expand shipyards, and industrial plants to

07:26.797 --> 07:47.421
accommodate this comprehensive shipbuilding 
program involving over 40,000 contractors, and

07:26.797 --> 07:47.421
sizable appropriations were made to the Bureau of 
Ships' extensive training program, which

07:26.797 --> 07:47.421
involved 2,000 military and 4,000 civilian 
personnel, and to the elaborate design program

07:26.797 --> 07:47.421
involving 161 different types of vessels. 
Production was concerned with the construction

07:47.401 --> 08:13.932
of 1,141 combatant vessels, 75,113

07:47.401 --> 08:13.932
landing craft, 519 auxiliaries, which together 
with other types totaled 98,131

07:47.401 --> 08:13.932
vessels of 7,465,046 tonnage. produced during 
the war years. In addition, 1,504 ships totaling

08:16.645 --> 08:28.377
over four and one half million tons were 
converted, while almost 1,200 ships of one third

08:16.645 --> 08:28.377
million tonnage were acquired. Peak production 
for one month was reached in May 1944, when 4,475

08:29.487 --> 08:40.825
vessels and craft were constructed and 30 million 
diesel horsepower were installed. Compare this

08:41.746 --> 08:52.643
with the Navy on 7 December 1941, which included 
only 4,000 ships with 16 million steam and diesel

08:41.746 --> 08:52.643
horsepower. It is of interest to compare the 
following figures showing the building periods

08:53.416 --> 08:58.784
required for specific types of vessels. 
According to the maximum period, the average

08:59.565 --> 09:08.138
period, and the estimated average Japanese 
period, a conservative estimate must be accepted

08:59.565 --> 09:08.138
with reservation. Battleships maximum 46, 
average 36, Japanese 48. Destroyers maximum 30,

09:14.708 --> 09:18.714
average 12, Japanese 24. Submarines 27, average 
11, Japanese 12. LST, maximum nine, average

09:24.485 --> 09:27.550
three.

09:31.336 --> 09:32.437
These must be months.

09:35.903 --> 09:48.583
Electronics production proved almost as 
spectacular with the manufacture of 35,617

09:35.903 --> 09:48.583
radar, radio, and sound equipment during the war 
years, plus 10,225 units for the Marine Corps.

09:49.508 --> 09:59.232
Maintenance involved the production of varying 
quantities of over 2,500,000 individual service

09:49.508 --> 09:59.232
parts requiring 227 acres of warehousing. 
Although repair and overhaul estimates are

09:59.600 --> 10:08.371
impossible to bring under a common denominator, 
it may be roughly estimated that over 20,000 ships

09:59.600 --> 10:08.371
were serviced each year. Over 500 calls for 
salvage were answered, resulting in the saving of

10:09.272 --> 10:15.661
$700 million worth of shipping. Finally, the 
vital and important post-war program includes

10:16.442 --> 10:23.110
$20 million appropriate for the preservation of 
the reserve fleet. The principal objective and

10:25.773 --> 10:37.825
motivation for this study, however, is not to 
eulogize the accomplishment of the personnel of

10:25.773 --> 10:37.825
the Bureau, rather it is to gather up a summary of 
past experience from which data may be drawn as a

10:25.773 --> 10:37.825
basis in the formulation of future plans. It makes 
several general considerations, which I need not

10:39.026 --> 10:54.362
go into here, but are worth reading, and the book 
itself is far from negligible, and I will repeat

10:39.026 --> 10:54.362
